<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P14">Race and ethnicity were collected for individuals based on the categories devised by the U.S. Office of Management and Budget (OMB) (<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">About Race—Census Bureau, n.d.</a>). <a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a> describes the race and ethnicity of the eyeGENE cohort. Most participants (4,483; 70%) are non-Hispanic or Latino, White. Hispanic and Latino participants represent approximately 10% (612) of the cohort. Four hundred and eighty-six (8%) participants are Black or African American, 350 (5%) are Asian, and 34 (0.5%) are American Indian or Alaska Native. One hundred and eleven (2%) people identified as more than one race. The remaining 10% of the cohort are unknown or did not report race and ethnicity. These cohort characteristics roughly represent the demographics reported in the 2019 U.S. census (<a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">Quick Facts—United States, n.d.</a>).</p>
